{
  "doc_id": "47717",
  "text": "The physiological functions of AS160 and Tbc1d1 in glucose and energy homeostasis have been investigated using whole body AS160 knockout [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , Tbc1d1 knockout [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , and AS160 knockin mice [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . These studies, consistent with differential expression of AS160 and Tbc1d1, identified different adipocyte-and skeletal muscle-specific defects in GLUT4 subcellular distribution and expression and glucose uptake and different defects in whole body glucose homeostasis in AS160-and Tbc1d1-mutant mice. No compensatory increases in Tbc1d1 and AS160 expression and phosphorylation were observed in AS160 and Tbc1d1 knockout mice, respectively (3, 4, 9, 17, 30, 32, 36). To investigate possible redundant functions for AS160 and Tbc1d1, we gen-erated and analyzed double-knockout mice for the two Rab GAPs (AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ /Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice). While our study was ongoing, another group published the characterization of male AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ /Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ mice (3). We found similar but also different abnormalities between our mice and those in the previously published AS160 Ϫ/Ϫ /Tbc1d1 Ϫ/Ϫ study, leading us to different conclusions on the relative roles of AS160 and Tbc1d1. In addition, we also analyzed female AS160",
